I've heard so many people swear about the importance of not eating past a certain time of the day to allow for WeightLoss to occur. I always ask them, who told you that? Would you believe I've tracked it down to Oprah Winfrey herself? In the late 80s when Oprah Winfrey lost weight, one of the times she lost weight, she told people she stopped eating after 4 PM. Some people took this at face value, and thought the key to weight loss is not eating past 4 PM, when in fact all she was doing was eating less calories over the course of the day. If you eat 3000 cal before 4 PM, versus eating 3000 cal spread evenly over the course of the day, you might even be worse off with the 4 PM fasting version. Bottom line, it's what you eat, and how much you eat. These are the most important factors.

Hot yoga. Hot Pilates. Heated dance cardio. Warm Spin studios. Everywhere you turn, there's a boutique studio fitness class turning up the temperature and leaving you a sweaty, disgusting mess by the end of your workout. But it's not actually helping you reach your weight-loss goals (if weight loss is your goal, that is). "Exercising in a cool environment actually contributes to greater caloric expenditure than exercising in a warm environment," celebrity trainer Harley Pasternak, MSc, told POPSUGAR. The New York Times bestselling author was debunking fitness myths left and right at the Fitbit summit in New York last week, and he gave us some details on why a cold workout is more optimal. "There's no need to be in a hot room and having your shirt dripping in sweat in order to burn fat," he said. "You burn way more fat in a cold room than in a hot room, [because] exercising in a cooler environment is more conducive to caloric expenditure and fat metabolism.
His claims are rooted in and backed by science; a 1997 study showed how cooler temperatures can combat obesity, and a 2014 study showed that "cold exposure increases energy expenditure." We also know that cold temperatures promote the increase of brown fat in the body — the "good kind" of fat to have — which can increase your metabolism.

One of the best ways you can try this is by getting outside. "Now that we're heading into Fall or Winter, don't be afraid to go outside and go for a great walk; there's no better time to do it," Harley said. "We're approaching the season where there's nothing better [for your health] than a brisk evening walk." Or you can follow Harley's own method and walk early in the morning (when it's cool) to go get your coffee — and your 10,000 steps.
So does this mean we have to skip hot yoga? "Don't skip Bikram yoga if you really enjoy and it makes you really happy," he said, "but don't look at it as a place where you're going to be burning calories. The hot temperature is about keeping your muscles loose and pliable, not to burn more calories".

Do you weigh yourself every day? Personally, I've never weighed a client in over 25 years in practice. People fixate too much on the number on the scale and feel defeated if that number does not drop, or even worse, goes up a pound or two. Keep in mind, you do not have direct control over your weight. You only have indirect control. As a byproduct of doing the things you have control over, hitting your step goal every day, getting enough sleep, eating well, you will indirectly change the number on the scale. So forget the number on the scale, and aside from being happy with how you look and how you feel, focus on the number of steps you have each day, the number of quality hours of sleep each night, and the number and type of calories you and just each day.

The keto diet is as divisive and polarizing as politics (if not more so). As it turns out, carbohydrates have the ability to really turn people against each other; those who are pro-keto (and seeing positive effects from the diet) would be quick to shut down anyone who said the diet isn't healthy, and those who don't subscribe to the ketogenic way of life would be dismissive of anyone who told them to stop eating carbohydrates.

That said, celebrity trainer and nutritionist Harley Pasternak, MSc, is never afraid to share his opinion on food, no matter the controversy surrounding a topic — he'll tell you that your dairy-free yogurt isn't healthy, your juice cleanse is BS, or that your "acai is a scam." So of course, we had to ask him about his thoughts on the keto diet. "Bad, bad, bad," he told POPSUGAR. "[Keto] is based on interesting, small bits of scientific evidence," he said, citing that "the research is actually done in animals," and in mice, specifically. He expanded on his thoughts of the diet and lifestyle, saying "it's antisocial, [and] it makes you have terrible breath." Harley also warned against the concept of fasting with the keto diet. "You're cannibalizing and metabolizing your lean tissue, your healthy tissue in your body," he said. "Life is too short; embrace it," he said. His parting words of nutritional wisdom? "Find balance, moderation. Eat food that makes you happy and healthy . . . but eat!"

My 4 sleep hacks. First, sleep with a Fitbit to analyze your duration and quality of sleep, then get suggestions of when the ideal time to go to sleep and wake up is based on your sleep patterns. Second, eye mask. It blocks out any ambient light that might sneak into the room and actually affect your quality and quantity of sleep. Third, ear plugs. An ambulance driving by in the middle of the night or an air conditioning unit on the roof turning on can actually wake you up if you’re not wearing your plugs. And forth, I sleep with a sound machine. I got the idea after watching how well my kids slept with sound machines. It creates an incredible ambient background white noise which blocks out anything that might be stressful. Somehow, through all of these things, I can still hear my kids calling for me in the middle of the night. luckily nothing blocks that out. 😴

How to buy seafood. Seafoods has had a tough time in the media lately with a lot of hokey documentaries trying to convince people that eating fish will kill them. This couldn't be further from the truth. Seafood is one of the best forms of protein and healthiest forms of fat you could possibly put in your body. The key to finding quality seafood is obeying the following three criteria. First, buy wild. Whenever possible wild seafood is a better way to go than farmed seafood. Next, buy domestic. If you happen to be lucky enough to live near water and have a local fisherman bring you their daily catch, fantastic. At the very least, try and stick to seafood that's been caught within your country. 90% of the seafood consumed in the United States is imported from countries with very lax guidelines for fishing. Third, stick to small seafood. The bigger the Fish the more mercury, the smaller the fish, less mercury. Think of scallops, shrimp, sardines, squid, and any and all freshwater fish you can think of.

Any single ingredient that is touted as a cure all elixir, should be examined very critically. Apple cider vinegar has been associated with nonsupported claims for weight loss, digestive health, skin health, and dozens of other health benefits. The truth is, there is very little evidence to support any of these claims. There is evidence, however, showing that chronic use of apple cider vinegar can lead to tooth decay and digestive issues. On a positive note, there have been a couple of studies that showed some promise with the use of small amounts of vinegar a day on insulin, blood sugar, and possibly weight loss. It's important to note that the benefits associated with vinegar use, or more about all vinegars, and not specific to apple cider vinegar. Chinese medicine has long espoused the use of small amounts of rice wine vinegar, Japanese chefs have been using vinegar as a key component to healthy meals for hundreds of years, and Mediterranean diets have always included aged balsamic vinegar to create healthy cooking. So, if you want to experiment with adding small amounts of vinegar in your diet, try adding some balsamic vinegar on your salad, or rice wine vinegar and dressings. It does not have to exclusively be through the use of apple cider vinegar.

Next time you exercise, focus on each individual set and each individual repetition. Feel your muscles, breathe, be present.

Misleading and false nutritional data on food labels. All too often we get taken advantage of by food manufacturers who trick us into thinking were eating less calories, sugar, or fat than we really are. It's up to you to critically examine these labels and decide for yourself. The simplest way to do so is multiply the carbohydrates by four then multiply the proteins by four then multiply the fat by nine. Add this number altogether, and this will give you the total calories per serving. You'll be shocked when you start doing this to the jars and containers and bottles in your fridge. At least half of them are off. The second thing to be aware of is how many servings in that package. Coconut water is one of the most guilty of products that I'm aware of, when they list only 40 cal per serving, then in small print it says 3.5 servings per bottle. And you end up drinking 35 g of sugar before you know it.

Is kale really a super food? The short answer is, no! While kale is healthy, and has a lot of great micronutrients, there are countless greens that are much healthier. Foods like watercress, Chinese cabbage, Chard, beet greens, spinach, leaf lettuce, Romain, collard greens, turnip green, mustard green, and endive, just to name a few, are all far more nutritionally dense than kale. Moreover, many of these taste a lot better and are easier to digest then kale. Covering kale with oil and baking to make chips, has become way to accepted, and is actually not far off from eating potato chips and french fries. So, if you love kale, keep eating kale. But if you're like me, and you don't really love kale, there are countless alternatives that are even healthier for you to consider.

Is açai worth it?
In my humble opinion, not really! This "cure-all", "super food" from the Amazon, got a lot of notoriety in the last 10 years when one small study showed that It was high in antioxidants. Well guess what, so are BlackBerries, blueberries, dark chocolate, artichokes, and dozens of other foods that are incredibly easy to get, taste great, and won't break the bank. But what concerns me the most, is 99% of the time, Açai berries are actually just the skin of the fruit, blended up with a bunch of sugar, heavily processed, frozen in small packages, and shipped to us in North America, Europe, and Asia. The truth is, Açai paste, and yes it really is just a paste, tastes very very bad. So the manufacturers add a ton of sugar in the processing of the fruit before they package it. Then, to make matters worse, people go to restaurants and order an açai bowl, that's loaded with tons of more sugar in the form of granola, and tropical fruits to make this purple paste taste delicious. People don't realize these quasi-healthy açai bowls, are giant sugar bombs. That being said, I say is definitely not bad for you, and still has some nutritional benefits. So if you're looking for a low guilt dessert, have a small açai bowl. If you're looking to replace a balanced meal with an açai bowl,think again.

Is salt really bad for you? The answer is no! Salt has been demonized over the last 25 years unnecessarily. Some very old, outdated studies which showed a small increase in blood pressure with the consumption of huge amounts of salt were the basis of nearly 3 decades of fear mongering. A recent meta-analysis, a collection of hundreds of studies in the past, demonstrated that there is no link between salt consumption and poor health. Research was unable to establish a link between eating more salt and getting more heart disease or strokes. In fact, recent research actually demonstrated a decrease in blood pressure, and some actual Weight loss with the addition of small amounts of salt to your existing diet. The caveat to this is if you have kidney problems or other health issues that your doctor has warned you about, but if you're a healthy person, do not fear salt.

Do sore muscles equal a great workout? The answer is, you do not need to be sore to have had an effective workout. Many people used to attribute muscle soreness to a buildup of lactic acid after an intense workout. We now know that this is not the case. Muscle soreness tends to peak around 48 hours after a workout, and is a result of creating small tears in your muscle fibers. This trauma can actually be a good thing, and Ideally will recover as a stronger/ fitter muscle. However, you do not need to be sore to accomplish this. Moreover, excessive muscle soreness can be a bad thing, and actually hinder your ability to do future workouts effectively. Bottom line, while you don't need to be sore to have had a good workout, a little soreness is OK, a lot is not.

Should we focus on the glycemic index when trying to lose weight? Not really! The glycemic index is a measure of the impact of certain ingredients on our blood sugar. We have been told for a long time that foods like white rice and potatoes will make us fat because they have a high glycemic index. The reality is we very rarely eat ingredients on their own. The combination of protein, or fiber, or fat to a meal will lower the glycemic index. When was the last time you ate a bowl of white rice by itself as a meal? Most likely, you would have a stirfry on top with vegetables and chicken. Moreover, a recent study published examining the dietary practices of women eating either a high glycemic or low glycemic index diet over 18 months, found no difference in weight loss. Your focus should be on making sure you have the holy Trinity of satiety and metabolism with each meal…… Protein, fiber, and healthy fats....and don't let white rice scare you!!

🍩 DO CARBS MAKE US FAT? 🍠
-
A very common statement is "I can't eat carbs. They make me gain weight." or "If I even think about chocolate cake, I gain 10 pounds." etc. etc.
-
When most of us think about carby foods, we tend to think of all our favorites like: 🍰 cake
🥐 croissant
🍟 fries
🍕 pizza
🍩 donuts
-
But when you look at the fat content of these foods -- it can make up as much as half the calories (or more). Just look above in my example. Most donuts are fried and that's what makes them so tasty. Half of the calories are fat from the oil and batter.
-
And then other foods like potatoes🥔, sweet potatoes🍠, rice 🍚, veggies 🥕🥒🥗, and fruits 🍒🍊🍍 are mostly all carbohydrates. But these foods on their own rarely taste good without at least a little fat. A baked potato is always better with a pat of butter or sour cream. A salad isn't too tasty unless it has some dressing (that usually contains fat). -
➡️ SO WHAT'S THE DEAL?
-
At the end of the day, when people say "carbs make me fat" a better statement would be "carbs and fat mixed together in foods that are super easy to overeat on make me fat."
-
Any excess of food, be it fat, carbs or protein will cause weight gain. Calories matter. But it's way easier to over eat on the donuts, cake, fries and buttery bread than it is on large amount of rice, veggies, or sweet potatoes.
-
300g of sweet potatoes with a pat of butter and a dash of cinnamon would still be fewer calories and less fat than a large donut that you could easily eat 2 or 3 of in one sitting.

No need to shun gluten if you don’t have celiac disease, study suggests
Research we're watching

Gluten, a storage protein in wheat, rye, and barley, triggers inflammation and intestinal damage in people with celiac disease. Due to concern that gluten may also increase the risk of obesity, diabetes, and cardiovascular disease among healthy people, the number of people without celiac disease who have adopted a gluten-free diet grew more than threefold from 2009 to 2014.

A team led by researchers from Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health used 20 to 30 years of data from the 64,714 women in the Nurses' Health Study and the 45,305 men in the Health Professionals Follow-up Study to examine the relationship of dietary gluten to the risk of chronic conditions such as coronary artery disease in people without celiac disease or heart disease. All the participants had completed questionnaires on their diet and health every four years from 1986 through 2010.

The team found no significant association between the participants' estimated gluten intake and their risk of developing coronary artery disease. Moreover, further analyses suggested that restricting dietary gluten may reduce a person's intake any of whole grains, which are associated with lower cardiovascular risk.

The authors point out that this is an observational study, so no firm conclusions can be drawn about cause and effect. Nevertheless, they conclude that their findings do not support the promotion of a gluten-restricted diet to reduce coronary artery disease risk. The results were published May 2, 2017, in The BMJ.

Being a parent has its challenges. Especially when it comes to creating good eating habits for our kids. In my experience, forbidding anything from your child's diet totally, can create some bad habits in the future. Teaching them how to responsibly include all sorts of foods in their diet, can prove helpful as they grow up. The video attached shows my daughter at a birthday party yesterday choosing between juice and cake. Yes, that's right, I said juice and cake. We teach our children that juice is a sweet indulgence to be had once in a while as a treat, not as a way of staying hydrated throughout the day. In fact, a large glass of apple juice or orange juice, may actually have far more sugar than any slice of birthday cake. Teach your children balance, moderation, and enjoyment when it comes to eating.

Is a raw diet better? The answer is NO!
Some people prefer to eat a diet where they do not cook their food. Not only does it significantly limit the amount of foods that you can eat, it poses a challenge when it comes to digestion and the bioavailability of many nutrients. Moreover, well over 48 million Americans per year get food poisoning, and you're really asking for it by not cooking your food at all. While there is some truth that over cooking your food is not a great idea, not cooking your food at all is not really the solution. Foods like tomatoes, carrots, zucchini, squash, and many others, are much healthier when you cook them. Bottom line, gently cook your foods, just don't over cook them.

Perfect example of why Japan is the healthiest country in the world. For those of you who read my book The World Diet, you know why I love the Japanese Diet. Last night we went to one of my favorite Japanese restaurants in Los Angeles, and had a very unlikely yet delicious dessert. I know it sounds strange, but purple Japanese sweet potato with frozen grapes and tapioca is now my absolute favorite dessert in the world. The restraint, precision, and focus on amazing ingredients, makes this Japanese indulgence, very low on my guilt meter. Now compare this to the typical desert you find out an American restaurant. Cheesecake factory comes to mind, probably 5000 times more calories than this piece of art.
